Ezemvelo KZN wildlife Multimedia &nbsp; &nbsp; User Galleries &nbsp; &nbsp; News in Pictures Send us your pictures &nbsp; &nbsp; Send us your stories Shocking footage shows a crocodile catching and eating a dog at Isimangaliso Wetlands Park in Kwa-Zulu Natal. Watch the footage here.WATCHPietermaritzburg -&nbsp;An illegal hunter who was found trespassing on iSimangaliso Wetland Park property last year was sentenced to 10 years in prison recently.A statement issued by the iSimanga&shy;liso Wetland Park said Musa Sibiya was sentenced to 10 years for the unlawful possession of a hunting rifle and nine live rounds of ammunition. Sibiya was sentenced to a further two years for trespassing, which runs concurrently with the 10-year sentence. &ldquo;The sentence sends a clear message to illegal hunters trespassing into South Africa&rsquo;s first world heritage site, the iSimangaliso Wetland Park,&rdquo; said iSimangaliso director Andrew Zaloumis.Sibiya (36), from Nongoma, and an unknown companion who evaded capture, entered iSimangaliso&rsquo;s uMkhuze section in October 2015 and was arrested by the Ezemvelo KZN Wildlife field rangers. &ldquo;He was in possession of a high- &shy;powered hunting rifle and silencer, live ammunition, an axe, hacksaw and binoculars,&rdquo; said Zaloumis.&ldquo;These are tools typically used for poaching black and white rhino.&rdquo;Zaloumis said the black rhino population in iSimangaliso&rsquo;s uMkhuze section is original &mdash; making it one of the most genetically valuable black rhino populations globally. &ldquo;Effective law enforcement is a critical part of our campaign to save these rhino. This conviction resulted from the good work of Ezemvelo rangers under very challenging conditions,&rdquo; he said.&mdash; Witness Reporter. 24.com encourages commentary submitted via MyNews24. Contributions of 200 words or more will be considered for publication.